  "summary": "At a rented apartment in Sheep's Pool Court, Mayfair, David Hunter and Rosaline discuss the extortion attempt by Inok Jacobson (also known as Enoch Yates). David expresses intense frustration, noting that the value of emeralds Rosaline previously sold to Greer-Trex has doubled, and he fears they will be \"bled dry\" by the blackmail. He expresses resentment over the secret struggle regarding Robert André, whom they had believed was dead in Africa. To manage the crisis and prevent Jacobson from approaching the Claude family, David plans to pay five thousand pounds to the man on Tuesday night. David adopts a defiant stance, instructing Rosaline to follow his directions exactly as part of his \"Enoch Yate Plan.\"\n\nMeanwhile, Rolly receives a letter on extravagant stationery from Beatrice Lippincott, a childhood acquaintance. The letter invites him to the Stagg to discuss matters regarding his late uncle's estate. Rolly decides to visit her at the pub, where Beatrice leads him into a private room. She informs Rolly that the gentleman he had previously inquired about, Mr. Yates, was visited the following evening by a Mr. Hunter. Beatrice further reveals that while performing her duties, she noticed a connecting door between Room 4 and Room 5 that is usually hidden by a large wardrobe, but noted that the door was slightly open during the time of the visit.",
